      "rationale": "Experimental test conditions for the bench-top hemolysis validation campaign (ValidationResult vr-hemolysis-bench-comparison) were documented with calibrated instrumentation. Flow rates controlled via Coriolis mass-flow meter (±0.15% FS); rotational speed via optical tachometer (±2 RPM); fluid temperature maintained at 37 ± 0.5°C using recirculating bath. Blood analog (bovine blood, hematocrit 30 ± 1%) batch characterization documented in lab notebook LN-2024-07. All five operating points replicated in triplicate; inter-replicate CV < 4%. Conditions match COU operating envelope."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/morrison/criteria/output-comparison-level2",
      "rationale": "Quantitative comparison of CFD-predicted NIH against experimental measurements performed using the validation metric of Oberkampf and Barone. Mean absolute relative error across 5 operating points: 8.3%. All predictions fall within the combined experimental and numerical uncertainty interval. Validation uncertainty (u_val) computed per ASME V&V 20-2009 and found to be 11.2% of the mean experimental value. The model error |E| = 8.3% < u_val = 11.2%, confirming the model is not invalidated at this COU. Comparison documented in ValidationResult vr-hemolysis-bench-comparison."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/morrison/criteria/qoi-relevance-level2",
      "rationale": "The primary QoI is the normalized index of hemolysis (NIH), which is the regulatory-accepted metric for blood trauma assessment per FDA guidance (FDA-2021-D-0886). Secondary QoIs include volume-averaged scalar stress and peak shear stress exposure time. These QoIs are directly linked to the COU decision criterion (RH < 1 relative to predicate). A formal QoI traceability matrix (ref: UofA-QoI-TM-2024) maps each computational output to the corresponding clinical endpoint and regulatory acceptance criterion, confirming full relevance."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/morrison/criteria/validation-relevance-level2",
      "rationale": "Validation activities were conducted on the FDA generic centrifugal blood pump geometry, which is the same platform as the COU device. Operating conditions in the validation campaign span the full COU flow-speed envelope (2–6 L/min, 2000–3500 RPM). Fluid properties (bovine blood analog, hematocrit 30%) are representative of clinical CPB conditions. The validation hierarchy (from component-level shear flow to system-level pump hemolysis) is documented in the V&V plan (ref: UofA-VVP-2024-01). Relevance score assessed as Gradation 2 — validation activities are directly representative of the COU without requiring significant extrapolation."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/morrison/criteria/solver-error-level1",
      "rationale": "Iterative convergence monitored for all simulations; residuals reduced by six orders of magnitude before solution extraction. Mass imbalance < 0.01% for all cases. Round-off error assessed via double-precision arithmetic throughout; no single-precision operations in the solution kernel. Solver log files archived and reviewed for anomalous convergence behavior. No divergence or stagnation events recorded across the 120 tolerance-sweep simulations. Achieved Gradation 2 exceeds MRL 2 requirement of Gradation 1."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/morrison/criteria/use-error-level1",
      "rationale": "Simulation setup was performed by a licensed CFD analyst with 8 years of rotating-machinery hemolysis modeling experience. A documented simulation protocol (ref: UofA-SP-2024-02) specifies all setup parameters including boundary condition assignment, turbulence model selection, rotating reference frame configuration, and hemolysis model constants. Independent peer review of the simulation setup was conducted by a second qualified analyst (ref: UofA-PR-2024-05). Discrepancies identified during review were resolved and documented. Use error risk assessed as low; Gradation 2 achieved."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/morrison/criteria/model-form-level2",
      "rationale": "The SST k-ω turbulence model was selected based on published benchmark studies for rotating blood-contacting devices (Ozturk et al., 2021; Hariharan et al., 2018) demonstrating superior performance relative to k-ε variants for adverse pressure gradient flows in pump geometries. The power-law hemolysis damage accumulation model (Giersiepen-Wurzinger correlation with Heuser-Opitz constants) is the regulatory-standard approach per FDA guidance. Model form uncertainty was assessed by comparing SST k-ω predictions against RSM and LES results on a representative impeller passage; NIH differences < 6%. Gradation 2 achieved, meeting MRL 2 requirement."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/morrison/criteria/model-inputs-level2",
      "rationale": "All model input parameters documented in the simulation data package (ref: UofA-SDP-2024-03). Fluid properties (density 1056 kg/m³, dynamic viscosity 3.5 mPa·s at 37°C) sourced from calibrated rheometry measurements on the blood analog batch used in validation. Boundary conditions (inlet flow rate, outlet pressure, rotational speed) set to match experimental conditions within instrument uncertainty. Geometric inputs derived from CMM-verified CAD model of the FDA generic CBP (dimensional tolerance ±0.05 mm). Hemolysis model constants sourced from published literature with uncertainty bounds propagated through the UQ analysis. Input uncertainty contribution to total output uncertainty: 14% of combined variance."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/morrison/criteria/test-samples-level2",
      "rationale": "The Test Samples factor addresses whether the physical specimens used in validation experiments are representative of the device population, including manufacturing variability, material batch effects, and sample-to-sample geometric variation. For this COU, the validation campaign employed a single FDA generic centrifugal blood pump specimen — a precision-machined reference artifact rather than a production-sampled device. This is a marginal scoping decision: at MRL 2 with Medium model influence and High decision consequence, a strict reading of ASME V&V 40 Table 4 suggests Gradation 2 would nominally require multi-specimen testing to characterize inter-unit variability. However, three converging justifications support scoping out this factor: (1) The FDA generic CBP is a standardized reference geometry, not a production device; its purpose is to serve as a computational and experimental benchmark, and inter-unit geometric variability is controlled to ±0.02 mm by the FDA reference protocol — an order of magnitude tighter than the dimensional tolerances under investigation in the COU. The specimen therefore represents the nominal geometry with high fidelity. (2) The COU decision criterion is relative hemolysis (RH < 1 vs. predicate), not absolute NIH certification. Because both the test device and predicate are evaluated against the same reference geometry and experimental baseline, specimen-to-specimen variability cancels to first order in the RH ratio. A sensitivity analysis (ref: UofA-SA-2024-08) confirms that ±0.02 mm geometric perturbations of the reference specimen produce RH variation of < 0.01 units, well below the decision threshold. (3) The primary source of uncertainty in the COU is manufacturing tolerance variation of the production device, which is explicitly and comprehensively addressed through the 120-run Latin hypercube tolerance sweep (ValidationResult vr-tolerance-sweep). This sweep directly characterizes the population of possible device geometries and identifies the worst-case hemolysis condition, fulfilling the substantive intent of the Test Samples factor for the COU decision. Scoping out Test Samples is therefore assessed as appropriate and conservative: the factor's underlying concern — that uncharacterized sample variability could invalidate the validation evidence — is demonstrably not a risk pathway for this COU given the reference-geometry experimental design and the explicit tolerance UQ campaign. This determination was reviewed and concurred with by the independent peer reviewer (ref: UofA-PR-2024-05, Section 4.3)."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/morrison/criteria/input-equivalency-level2",
      "rationale": "Equivalency between validation experiment inputs and COU simulation inputs was evaluated systematically for all primary input parameters. Flow rate, rotational speed, fluid temperature, and hematocrit were matched within instrument uncertainty across all five validation operating points. The validation geometry (FDA generic CBP reference artifact) is dimensionally equivalent to the nominal COU device geometry within CMM measurement uncertainty. A formal input equivalency matrix (ref: UofA-IEM-2024-01) documents each input parameter, its value in the validation experiment, its value in the COU simulation, the difference, and the associated uncertainty. No input parameter exhibits a systematic offset exceeding its combined uncertainty. Equivalency assessed at Gradation 2, meeting MRL 2 requirement."
    }
